You want to use the [readline][1] library. Supporting for up arrow (and many other additional key bindings) does not exist with standard I/O, but it is readily available with [readline][1].

Also note that your program should loop over the input, instead of making recursive calls between main and parse.
~~~
   // This is prog.c
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;
#include &lt;readline/readline.h&gt;
#include &lt;readline/history.h&gt;

void parse(char* command){
    if(!strcmp(command,&quot;exit&quot;)){
        exit(1);
    }
}

int main (int argc, char* argv[]){
    char *buffer;

    while ((buffer = readline(&quot;command &gt;&quot;)) != NULL) {
        add_history(buffer);
        parse(buffer);
        free(buffer);
    }
    return 0;
}

~~~
You will have to build with `readline`:
~~~
cc prog.c -lreadline
~~~

For more information about `readline` please refer to this [`link`](https://tiswww.case.edu/php/chet/readline/rltop.html)

[1]: http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/readline.3.html

